    # [Scene: Municipal Hall | Afternoon]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quickening, bright strings underscored by low percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A cluster of camera shutters; polite applause; the rustle of papers]
    "The ink is still drying on the contract when Cass places the tablet on the table between you and Mayor Lynette. The boardroom smells of warm coffee and the metallic tang of too-new pens. Mayor Lynette's"
    "grin is camera-perfect, the kind of expression that reads like a promise on campaign posters."
    show mayor_lynette_cole at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lynette_cole "This is what I like to call progress, folks. Steady funding, transparent milestones. We did it."
    "You feel the moment like a small wave underfoot — a steady, welcome push after months of paddling. The room hums: reporters murmuring, staffers confirming schedules, the town's immediate future being annexed into spreadsheets and timetables."
    "On the tablet, the models rotate in precise steel-blue: revetments hugging the shoreline, modular seawalls that flex with tidal data, pump arrays mapped to older stormwater channels."
    show cassian_cass_romano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "We can start deployment within two weeks if the permits clear. I'll make sure the crews use the material mixes we tested in the field trials."
    "He does not sound like a salesman right now. His voice is low, close enough that the salt on his skin — a city salt, manufactured by plane and machine — is almost an afterthought. His"
    "hand hovers toward the tablet and then finds the back of your chair, an almost-accidental clasp on your shoulder. The gesture is furtive, human — the kind of contact that says we'll stand through the weather"
    "together, even if we disagree about the forecast."
    show mira_kestrel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We need community seats at every stage. Implementation matters as much as the plan."
    "Cass's jaw tightens in that familiar line of control, then relaxes as he nods."

    cassian_cass_romano "Agreed. You and Dr. Saira will lead the monitoring panels. Transparency is... non-negotiable, Mira. I mean it."
    "His words land heavier than the handshake that follows. Around you, the boardroom chatter swells into a congratulatory tide. The cameras find Mayor Lynette again; she leans in, radiant and practiced for the frame. The municipal scaffolding of promises glints under the presentation lights."

    "Dr. Saira N'Goma" "Mira, once the forms are signed we'll cross-validate the load models with the marsh data. If the sensors show unexpected subsidence we'll adapt the sequencing."
    "You nod, fingers pressed to your coral pendant, feeling its familiar weight against wind-rough skin."

    menu:
        "Lean into Cass's shoulder":
            "You let your weight slide closer, a brief, disarming human moment. Cass's hand tightens for a heartbeat; an unspoken acknowledgement passes between you."
        "Step back and focus on the tablet":
            "You pivot toward the tablet, fingers tracing the 3D edges of the planned revetment. Your posture says professionalism. Cass watches you, respect edged with something like hunger."

    # --- merge ---
    "Cass glances at you, then at the room. Professionalism re-claims the space. Cameras flash; Mayor Lynette commands a final photo. It feels like a victory — and, between the lines of press releases, a precarious one."
    "You tuck the tablet under your arm when the crowd thins, and for the first time in months your shoulders loosen in the way that comes before sleep."
    # [Scene: Research Lighthouse | Early Evening]
    hide mayor_lynette_cole
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano with rising arco strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain beginning to patter on the roof; distant machinery from the docks]
    "You bring the tablet up to the lighthouse because the light is honest here, and because the instruments hum a reliable rhythm you trust. The wind tugs at your jacket hem; the smell is wet algae and diesel and something that tastes like possibility."
    "You sit at the metal table and let the models spin. Cassian's renderings are clinical and sure: cross-sections that take account of wave refraction, load-bearing pylons spaced on scientifically determined intervals, panels that lock together like"
    "vertebrae. The color palette is businesslike — slate, steel, careful cyan highlights. Yet when you zoom into the nodes where human use interacts with engineered barrier, your stomach tightens. Cultural access points. Boat launches. The old"
    "rope-and-shell moorings."
    "Your phone buzzes with a string of congratulatory texts. Tessa sends an excited emoji. Old Man Rafi leaves a voicemail that sounds like prayer and a promise. Jonah's message is a single word: Watch."
    "Cass lingers in the doorway for a long beat before he steps inside. He leaves the heavy door open so the rain sings across the turret and his shoulders look narrower in the shelter of the lab light."
    show cassian_cass_romano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "You look tired."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We all do. It's been a long—"

    cassian_cass_romano "—year. I know. I wasn't sure you'd take the partnership."
    "Your throat tightens. Partnership had sounded like a clean meeting of minds; it has turned into a knot of concessions, promises, and the private arithmetic of what you could risk."

    mira_kestrel "I took it because I want people to be safe, Cass. Because I think engineering can help if it listens."
    "Cass moves to the table and, unprompted, sets his hand flat on the tablet screen. The gentle press distorts the holograph for a second. His fingers are cool, precise."

    cassian_cass_romano "I didn't come here to bulldoze your community. I came because —' (he laughs, a brittle sound) '— because I was tired of seeing places like this disappear. And because I kept thinking, if we don't build a model town that doesn't lose what makes it human, who will?"
    "His eyes flick to yours, steel-gray made soft by the lamplight. His lapel pin glints; for the first time, the polish seems like armor rather than identity."

    cassian_cass_romano "I'm afraid, Mira. Of failing. Of being the reason another family loses what they can't replace."
    "The confession lands like a struck bell. It's raw and immediate and unknown to the polished man the town sees at meetings."
    "You didn't expect to hear fear from someone who sells certainty. It shifts the whole geometry between you. Fear means stakes; fear means he can be wrong. Fear means he understands loss."

    mira_kestrel "What are you afraid of, really? Losing your career? Being blamed? Or losing people?"
    "Cass looks away, fingers tracing a line on the laminated map as if mapping an unknown fault."

    cassian_cass_romano "All of it. But mostly —' (he meets your gaze) '— being the person who promised a fix and watched it fail."
    "The rhythm of the instruments fills the silence. Dr. Saira's voice hums in your memory: adapt with humility. Cass's admission is the humility of a man who has practiced control and found it brittle."

    cassian_cass_romano "I want to do this with you, Mira. Not over you."
    "The difference between with and over is a small word with big teeth. You let the word settle between you like a shared map."

    menu:
        "Ask him to show you the risk models":
            "You lean in, voice steady. Cass taps a layer and lines appear — stress tolerances, worst-case returns. He explains anchor torque like a teacher, voice warmed by purpose."
        "Reach for his hand and hold it":
            "You find his fingers across the table and squeeze. His surprise is small, then returns in a smile that breaks the engineer's hardness for a second. The models keep spinning, but the room shifts in scale toward just the two of you."

    # --- merge ---
    "Cass stays longer than necessary, talking through contingencies and hours, not just plans. He tells you about the prototypes they shelved after a field test in a different town; about panels that buckled when silt behaved"
    "unpredictably. He is precise and honest and, when he forgets to be guarded, human. You answer with what you know of the marsh's slow patience, of Old Man Rafi's lines on the tides, of the ways"
    "boats have been hauled to safer ground for generations."
    "The night bends into something that feels like confession disguised as work. You speak until you can feel your sentences braid into his. You trade data for memory. He admits a childhood fear of the ocean"
    "swallowing the pier his family built. You tell him about the storm that took your childhood bedroom and the sound that stayed behind."

    cassian_cass_romano "If it helps — I want to make sure the pier doesn't get swallowed again. I want it to be ours."

    mira_kestrel "Then make sure our people have a say."
    "He nods, and the nod is a promise."
    # [Scene: Docks — Crews Installing | Morning]
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Energetic percussion layered with hopeful brass]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammering, the thrum of pile drivers, the hiss of winches; gulls distant]
    "The construction starts fast and visible. Crews string formwork along the shoreline; steel pylons rise like new bones. The municipal scaffolding catches the morning sun and glints with professional polish. Trucks roll in, diesel and sand and men and women whose faces are intent. The town watches."
    "Jonah Reyes stands on the docks, a single silhouette against the milling activity. The rope-and-shell bracelet circles his wrist; his knuckles whiten around the rope. He doesn't call out. He watches, a quiet storm contained in amber eyes."
    "You walk the edge of the worksite because you need to see the contact points — where engineered assurance meets human use. The first handoff is always noisy: compromises are negotiated in rumble and grit."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "So this is the 'compromise' you chose."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "Jonah—"

    jonah_reyes "—Don't. Don't make that face. You watched the signatures. You helped them polish the edges."
    "Jonah's anger is tidal and patient; it isn't performative. It holds history and the smell of rope and fish and the feeling of a family rebuilding through sweat."

    mira_kestrel "I insisted on community oversight. I made them promise seats at the monitoring panel. This isn't a bulldoze-and-vanish plan."
    "Jonah Reyes shakes his head, eyes never leaving a crew hauling a reinforced panel past the launch."

    jonah_reyes "They still put a wall where the old launch was. There's a new line between boats and people."

    mira_kestrel "We can adapt the launch. We can design cutouts. We can—"

    jonah_reyes "Can we? Or will the plan slowly move our access away, mile by mile, until the pier is just a postcard?"

    mira_kestrel "You know I don't want to take that away from anyone. You know I chose community measures, even with them. I thought —"
    "Jonah's jaw works. There's a long silence, punctuated only by a crew's radio announcing a lift. The harbor smells of iron and salt and the newness of the day."

    jonah_reyes "I don't want to lose the town to nice-looking structures and meetings that say we saved everything. I want people to still come home wet and smelling of fish."

    mira_kestrel "So do I."

    jonah_reyes "Do you?"
    "The question is small and jagged. In it is everything you are balancing: livelihoods, heritage, the lives of people who taught you how to read a tide."
    "You step closer, and for a moment you think you'll reach out and catch him, tell him the compromises are temporary scaffolding, that you'll keep fighting. But the crew's radio screeches and the crane's thump pulls both of you back into the day's rhythm."

    menu:
        "Call out to him, namesake laughter to break the tension":
            "You call his name with the kind of laugh only he remembers. Jonah's mouth twitches; the tension deflates by a degree. He answers with a clipped grin that doesn't fully reach his eyes."
        "Stay silent and watch the crew work":
            "You let the silence sit between you, thick and honest. Jonah doesn't look away. The quiet says more than words."

    # --- merge ---
    "Jonah watches you walk toward the forms, the way you carry your weight between científica certainty and the wet, stubborn town. He doesn't follow. The distance between you is not just feet."
    # [Scene: Research Lighthouse | Night — Long Conversations]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rising piano motif with urgent strings; heartbeat-like low drums]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain on the roof, the soft click of the tablet, an occasional distant shout from the docks]
    "Nights at the lighthouse become a discipline. You sleep later, think longer, argue softer and with more hunger. Cass brings coffee and a stack of annotated sections. Dr. Saira swings by sometimes with tired, sharp eyes"
    "and a thermos of something bitter and hopeful. You find your conversations orbiting the same core: data, ethics, and the brittle intimacy that happens when two people build something together that could hurt as much as"
    "it could help."
    show cassian_cass_romano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "I ran stress loads tonight that should not have failed. They did, in iteration four. We caught it. We caught it because you insisted on the marsh test data."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We caught it because Old Man Rafi's tides don't follow neat distributions. The sensors pick up what models miss."

    cassian_cass_romano "We can tweak the anchors. We can alter the grain size of the fill. We can phase it so community launches are preserved. We can—"

    mira_kestrel "We can make choices that don't write off people's work."
    "Cass leans back, exhausted and defiantly vulnerable."

    cassian_cass_romano "I get up in the morning thinking about which bolt needs a different grade. I go to sleep thinking about whether a wrong calculation could make me the man who took a town's pier. I don't know how to be anything but useful."
    "You reach for him across the table, across the blinking cursor of a model, across the city-firm lines that shape him."

    mira_kestrel "You're not just useful, Cass. You're learning to share the work."
    "He laughs, a short, wet sound, and then something loosens — a confession not tied to engineering details."

    cassian_cass_romano "Sometimes I think the thing I want most is to stop being so sure about everything. To be allowed to be wrong in private and still wake up to try again."

    mira_kestrel "We're all trying. The models help. The people keep us honest."
    "Conversations wind into softer territory: childhood storms, the first time Jonah mended a net, the smell of the city salt in Cass's clothes. Words become touchpoints. You share the lighthouse's small meals. You talk about a"
    "future where pylons don't have to be knives across the water but a seam that people can work around."
    "When dawn finally finds you both, you are not lovers in some neat label, but you are close enough that the small gestures — a blanket thrown over knees, a cup placed within reach — feel electric."

    cassian_cass_romano "Will you sleep, Mira? Properly?"

    mira_kestrel "Tonight? Maybe. Maybe because I feel like we're moving somewhere."
    "He meets your gaze with an unguarded look and, for a breath, the world reduces to the hum of instruments, the harbor beyond the glass, and the feeling that you might be building more than walls together."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Climactic swell — strings and brass; the arousal reaches its apex]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The lighthouse foghorn, long and sure; a distant ship's horn answering]
    "You close your notebook and lay your hand flat on the tablet. The models are not finished; nothing is fully finalized. But there is movement, contract ink drying into action, crews that began the work and"
    "will continue tomorrow. For the first time in months, you feel exhaustion that is not hollow but dense with accomplishment. Sleep is no longer a luxury; it's a reset earned by sweat and negotiation."
    "You: (internal) Hope tastes like strong coffee, rain-warm and a little bitter. It tastes like shared fears laid on the table and the slow, steady work of shoring up what matters."
    "Outside, the harbor sighs. Jonah's lamp still burns on the docks like a watchful eye. You imagine the town waking to the sound of machines, to work that will bend its shoreline and its rhythms. You imagine conversations to come, easier and harder both."
    "A sense of fragile victory settles across your shoulders like a well-fitting coat. It's not total. It won't be quiet. But for the first time in months you sleep."
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle decrescendo into a single sustained chord]
    "You rest with the knowledge that the lines you've signed are more than ink — they're commitments that will be tested by salt and storm. You also carry the quieter knowledge that complicates every line: the people you love, the heritage at stake, and the inevitability of difficult choices ahead."
    # [Page-Turn Moment]

    "You wake before dawn with a tilt in your stomach that is not fear but the electric prickle of anticipation. In the hush, your phone lights with a single message thread labeled: Municipal Operations — new schematic uploaded. The subject line reads, in Mayor Lynette's clipped voice" "Final blueprints attached. Enactment begins Monday."
    "You stare at the message, the screen's glow drawing the same thin line across your face that the models have drawn across the map. The work you started with Cass is real and moving. Something else"
    "waits in that small attachment — decisions that will repeat the arguments you've had, and the ones you haven't yet had."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

